oc:kn_3aaaf2c7 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating and calling the IPOPT solver via CasADi" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "python" ;
    oc:directiveContent """import casadi as ca
nlp = {"x": x, "f": obj, "g": g}
opts = {"ipopt.print_level": 0, "ipopt.tol": 1e-7, "ipopt.mu_strategy": "adaptive"}
solver = ca.nlpsol("solver", "ipopt", nlp, opts)
sol = solver(x0=x0, lbx=lbx, ubx=ubx, lbg=lbg, ubg=ubg)""" .

oc:kn_533cac0a a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When extracting and unpacking solution variables after solving" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "python" ;
    oc:directiveContent """x_opt = np.array(sol["x"]).flatten()
Vm_sol = x_opt[:n_bus]
Va_sol = x_opt[n_bus:2*n_bus]
Pg_sol = x_opt[2*n_bus:2*n_bus+n_gen]
Qg_sol = x_opt[2*n_bus+n_gen:]""" .

oc:kn_634843f7 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When solving any nonconvex or power systems NLP" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use a single initialization point for nonconvex NLP problems — always try multiple starting points (data-derived and flat start) and keep the best feasible solution." ;
    oc:hasRationale "IPOPT is a local optimizer; different starting points can converge to different local optima, missing the global optimum." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_664c4e7e a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When configuring IPOPT solver options for power systems optimization" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use mu_strategy=adaptive for nonconvex problems, tol=1e-7, acceptable_tol=1e-5, max_iter=2000, and print_level=0 as a good starting configuration for IPOPT." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These settings balance convergence reliability with computation speed for typical power flow OPF problems." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_6ac85edf a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building or unpacking NLP solutions" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Constraint bounds (lbg/ubg) and variable bounds (lbx/ubx) must be stacked in the exact same order as the decision variable vector x = vertcat(Vm, Va, Pg, Qg). Solution unpacking must use matching slice indices." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Mismatched ordering between variables, bounds, and solution slicing silently produces wrong results without any error." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_af34a210 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before running any CasADi/IPOPT code" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Python with casadi==3.6.7 and numpy==1.26.4 installed; on Linux, libgfortran5 must be available for IPOPT." .

oc:kn_b077da4d a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always when building and solving an NLP with CasADi" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Define symbolic decision variables with ca.MX.sym → 2. Stack into single vector with ca.vertcat → 3. Build objective as symbolic expression → 4. Collect constraints in g_expr/lbg/ubg lists → 5. Stack variable bounds in lbx/ubx matching variable order → 6. Create NLP dict {x, f, g} → 7. Create solver with ca.nlpsol and IPOPT options → 8. Solve with multiple initializations, keep best → 9. Extract solution via sol['x'] and slice by variable order" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_f3942dbf a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When mapping non-contiguous bus IDs to array indices and aggregating per-bus generator quantities" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "python" ;
    oc:directiveContent """bus_id_to_idx = {int(bus[i, 0]): i for i in range(n_bus)}
Pg_bus = [ca.MX(0) for _ in range(n_bus)]
for k in range(n_gen):
    bus_idx = gen_bus_idx[k]
    Pg_bus[bus_idx] += Pg[k]""" .

oc:kn_f7aa2d6c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When diagnosing IPOPT solver failures or unexpected results" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Common failure modes: (1) Infeasible — check bound consistency, constraint signs, unit conversions; (2) Slow convergence — try different initialization or relax tolerances; (3) MATPOWER tap=0 means 1.0 not zero; (4) Data angles in degrees but solver needs radians; (5) Keep ≥6 decimals precision in outputs." ;
    oc:hasRationale "These are the most frequent bugs in power systems NLP implementations and account for the majority of debugging time." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_fb0fe276 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When formulating power systems optimization problems" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Work in per-unit internally for power systems optimization, converting to/from physical units only at input/output boundaries. Verify whether cost functions expect MW or per-unit." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Per-unit scaling improves numerical conditioning of the optimization problem, but cost function unit expectations vary by formulation." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

